        primaryBeneficiary: "Very low-income elderly",
        storyBlurb: "HUD's Section 202 program supports nonprofit entities in building and operating affordable housing for very low-income elderly tenants, with continued appropriations sought in the FY2026 Congressional Justification. The program has historically been one of the federal government's most targeted tools for addressing senior housing need, recognizing that elderly households on fixed incomes face acute affordability challenges that the private market cannot adequately address.\n\nSection 202 provides capital advances and project rental assistance to nonprofit sponsors, enabling them to develop and operate affordable housing for seniors without having to service conventional debt. This structure allows deeply subsidized rents that would be impossible under a standard tax-credit or market-rate development model, making Section 202 uniquely suited to serving the lowest-income elderly households.\n\nThe FY2026 budget request reflects HUD's ongoing commitment to the program despite broader federal budget pressures, including a lapse in appropriations reported in early February 2026 that temporarily affected HUD operations. Advocates for elderly Americans have consistently called for expanded Section 202 funding, citing a growing senior population and a pipeline of aging affordable senior housing that requires both preservation and new construction investment.",
